You have two solutions to your problem:

 **1. Render a `js.erb` template from your server**

A `js.erb` file contains javascript code that will we sent from the server and executed on the frontend. 

Simply put, instead of rendering classic HTML, the server will send back the javascript code you write in your `js.erb` file. The advantage of such an approach is that you can use ruby in your template and render your comments html instead of building it from scratch. (see the link to the rails docs below for more details)

In your controller:

```ruby
def show
  @comments = Comment.all

  respond_to do |format|
    format.js
    format.html
  end
end
```

In your `views/comments/show.js.erb` file (which will be render by the server):

```javascript
$(&quot;#comments&quot;).html(&#39;&lt;%= j render @comments %&gt;&#39;)
```

In your view `view/comments/show.html.erb`

```
function reloadComments() {
  $.ajax({
    type: &#39;GET&#39;,
    url: &#39;/comments&#39;,
    dataType: &#39;script&#39;
  })
}

// Trigger after loading the page
$(function() {
  setTimeout(reloadComments, 3000);
});
```

[More info in Rails docs here][1]

**2. Build the HTML template from your json data in your frontend javascript**

I won&#39;t put the code here but there&#39;s plenty of resources online and this is not the simplest approach regarding your issue.


  [1]: https://guides.rubyonrails.org/working_with_javascript_in_rails.html#server-side-concerns

